  "prompt": "Who discovered Avogadro's number?",
  "response": "Avogadro's number, also known as Avogadro's constant, is named after the Italian scientist Amedeo Avogadro. However, Avogadro himself did not determine the number; he only proposed the concept of the Avogadro's constant in 1811 when he hypothesized that equal volumes of gases at the same temperature and pressure contain the same number of molecules.\n\nThe actual value of Avogadro's number was first accurately estimated by the French physicist Jean Perrin in the early 20th century. Perrin's work involved a series of experiments using various methods, such as studying the Brownian motion of particles suspended in a liquid. For his contributions to this field, Perrin was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1926.",
